Not sure if this matters, but because you are doing your asyncs *after* the ones above vs. *nested inside* the ones above, there are no guarantees on which async handlers will run first.  Thus, it is possible that your async handler will run before the ones above.

I wanted to mention this due to the code in ~PowerMetrics():

        nlohmann::json& pc = asyncResp->res.jsonValue["PowerControl"];
        if (!pc.empty())

This seems to be assuming that some other code has already finished and added an element to the PowerControl JSON.

In practice, it may be that your new code will always run last, but I'm not sure that is guaranteed.  Probably depends on whether the D-Bus code enforces a FIFO ordering of handling requests.
